In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain persecuted more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, while at the same time 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the right hand finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was considered, as for 19 percent of those men whose rings and fingerprints were the same.
However, in men whose finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty-seven percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already in prenatal age, clearly reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones that the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer finger.
Previously research showed that the testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancers.
